column1: 0x4bd4afa9b213b5184c995aaef4982ce564121d20@RecoveryWithTenant: calls the ecrecover function  (which should correspond to a precompiled contract)
column2: additionally it calls a function (recover) of another contract (Destination) whose address is specified in a another function (configure) which however is subject to some access control that should protect the contract: There is a modifier checking that certain functionality can only be performed by an oracle (onlyOracle) that makes sure that certain options can only be performed by the oracle
column3: in particular the oracle (using the function setOracle) can only be set by the previous oracle. The oracle then can bypass the signature requirement in the configure function and hence can set the callDestination and the tenant. A call to the callDestination is then performed in recoverUser. This call however is guarded by the requirement to provide a valid signature by the current tenant with some unique nonce. The tenant however could have been also set in configure as wished (by the oracle). Hence giving such a signature is easily possible (for the oracle)
column4: resulting in a call that can easily callback which will cause a reentrancy according to our definition by e.g. being able to invoke a signature check (which is technically a call to a predefined contract)
column5: but also potentially to reach the same call again as the invoked contract could easily change the oracle + the tenant to match his address before performing the recoverUser() function again. Initially
column6: the oracle is set in the constructor to be the creator of the contract. So basically
column7: the creator of a contract could perform a reentrancy attack (or at least he could easily by making someone else the oracle enable this attack)@unsafe@yes@insecure @ Safe@1@0@0@1@0@0@0@0@1
